Durban - Thousands of security officers are set to take to the streets in planned marches around the country on Tuesday. The marches, orchestrated by the Motor Transport Workers Union (MTWU) – an affiliate of the Federation of Unions of South Africa (Fedusa) in cash-in-transit industry is to demand an end of the scourge of cash-in-transit attacks that have plagued the country in recent weeks. 

According to Fedusa, the heists especially Gauteng, Mpumalanga and KwaZulu Natal has reached crisis levels in recent months; hitting the 159 in the first six months this year compared to 147 for entire year in 2017.AdChoicesADVERTISINGinRead invented by Teads

In Durban, the Fedusa is expecting hundreds of officers to gather at the Gugu Dlamini Park in Durban Central from 8:30am. Marchers will then proceed along  Masabalala Yengwa Avenue and right into Somtseu Road  towards Hoy Recreational Park where they will hand over a Memorandum of Demands to the Provincial Police Commissioner. 

In Jhb, an estimated 1 000 MTWU members accompanied by 60 armoured cash trucks will depart from 20 De Korte Street in Braamfontein at 9:30am and proceed down Jorissen, Bicaard and Simmonds Streets to Bayers Naude Square in the CBD where a Memorandum of Demands will be handed over to Sizakele Nkosi-Malobane, Gauteng MEC for Security and Safety. 

In Cape Town, the processions accompanied by four trucks will depart from Keizergracht at 10am in Cape Town central, move down Darling Street, turn into Adderley Street, head towards Wale Street and end at Western Cape Provincial Parliament where a Memorandum will be handed over.

In Bloemfontein, marchers accompanied by 15 trucks, will gather at Mahunger at 7am and then proceed along Mandela Street, Magraf and finally into Charlotte Maxeke Street towards the Provincial Commissioner’s Office where they will hand-over the Memorandum

And in Nelspruit, marchers accompanied from GF4S Offices at 6am will move to the Rugby Stadium before proceeding towards Nelspruit Police Station where they will hand over the Memorandum to the Provincial Police Commissioner.

